time in south and east india. european traders started visiting india beginning in the late 16th century. prominent among these were the british, french and the portuguese. the british east india company made calcutta their headquarters in 1772. they also established subsidiary cities like bombay and madras. calcutta later went onto to become 'the second city of the empire after london'. by the 19th century, the british had, one way or the other assumed political control of virtually all of india, though the portuguese and the french too had their enclaves along the coast. there was an uprising by indian 